Financial Analysis - A food delivery dataset

Financial analysis of an E-commerce company with a missing business model and without knowing any best practices. Exploratory analysis done in Google Sheets, incl. line item mapping based on IFRS related assumptions. Finishing with a gross profit calculation, company health analysis, explanation profit decreasing critical errors in software and recommending operational improvements.

You can download the Excel file here:

GitHub
Bettina Bujna
Some guidelines:
1. Assumptions: Feel free to make assumptions when you encounter unclear or insufcient information while
constructing the nancial statements. Ensure that you document these assumptions.
2. Software Usage: You can utilize any software programs you prefer, and Excel is entirely acceptable for this
task.
3. Transparency: It is crucial to present your work clearly, encompassing your methodology, steps, and any
assumptions you make.
PART 1
Generate a Prot and Loss (P&L) report for management, up to the Gross Prot line. Make sure to exhibit
your calculations and specify any assumptions you rely on. Not all provided facts may pertain to the P&L.
The attached database is a Monthly Report on Deliveries in Month X (in cents) - Comprehensive records
of all deliveries made during Month X.
Additional Information:
1. Customers place orders for food delivery via Foodpanda and pay through a card processor company. Apart
from the cost of the food, customers are charged a 5 delivery fee (9 for orders exceeding 100), applicable
taxes, and tips.
2. Restaurants featured on the Foodpanda platform are categorized as partners or non-partners. Foodpanda
remunerates partner restaurants on a weekly basis through card transfers, withholding our commission.
3. In Month X, we acquired 1,000 new customers through referrals. Existing customers can receive a 5
discount on delivery charges for each new customer they refer who subsequently registers through their
referral link.
4. Couriers are responsible for delivering food from restaurants to customers and receive payment (via card
transfers) comprising a 5 delivery fee and 100% of the customer's tip for their services.
5. We incur support costs at a rate of 0.50 per delivery.
6. We pay our card processor a fee amounting to 1.8% of the order value, plus 0.40 for each delivery.
1

- We are in Month X
- Normal delivery fee = 5 EUR, Big delivery fee (over 100 EUR Food total) = 9 EUR
- Partner restaurants are paid on a weekly basis through card
- Withholding our commission: when we receive payments from customers a commission is charged
- Before transferring the earnings to restaurants, I assume we deduct this fee from the order value
- In this month we have 1000 new customers through referrals
- Old customers delivery discount is 5 EUR / 1 new customer
- Couriers paid 5 EUR / delivery + 100% of tips
- Support cost paid 0.50 EUR / delivery
- Card processing fee = 1.8% of order value + 0.40 EUR per delivery

amounts in euro cent
- ID: has no duplicates, is a sequence for each line item
- Food: net amount of food prices, other special items described in the Assumptions section
- Tax: tax amount, varies per food groups
- Delivery fee:
- Service fee: paid by customers when placing an order
5 EUR / delivery (or 9 EUR if Food total > 100 EUR)
- Unique percentage fees: bug or hard deliveries? (pls see Assumptions section)
- Tips: fully adjustable and collected from customers, paid in 100% to couriers
- Commission fee:
- Partner restaurants: fee is 0 for line items, SUM paid by Foodpanda weekly
- Non-Partner restaurants: fee varies for each restaurant
- Ination = inated amount of net food + tax rate, each food group has a predetermined ination rate per
month to adjust our dataset to current prices
- Discount:
- Referral: 5 EUR / new referral on delivery fee
- Partial: varies for each order
- Full: customer pays nothing, we get commission, no card cost
- Refund: full or partial refunds paid back to customers with ination, we get commission, has
card cost

ASSUMPTIONS
1. The delivery fee can be 0 assuming a campaign for free delivery (because there was no info if
there is an option for pick-up).
2. Delivery (service) fee is not subject to tax, Tax column does not contain this fee.
3. When delivery fee amounts are not 0, 5 or 9 EUR, they have a tendency to be 7, 9, 10 or 17% of
the Food column. Im not really sure if this is a bug, as the task clearly states that these fees
should be xed amounts.
There are 32 line items with these unique delivery fees - including rows where there is no tax -
which I choose to leave in the dataset for further analysis (pls see #4).
4. There are orders when the Tax amount is 0 (without full refund/discount) and there is no delivery
fee, which I assume is the partner restaurants remuneration as this is the only scenario I can think
of where the tax is considered outside of the company.
The card processor cost is 0 on these partner restaurant remunerations, paid in a sum and are not
calculated for each line item.
This strengthens the theory of not having just the food delivery orders as line items. Meaning
that we need to analyze further each and every outstanding line item.
a. [Tax] = 0 AND [Delivery fee] = 0
Remuneration to partner restaurants (7 line item).
b. [Tax] = 0 AND [Delivery fee] 0, 5 or 9 EUR
15 line items just with Food total and Delivery fee (~9 or ~18% of the Food total).
I'll assume these are re-deliveries. Maybe the bigger delivery fee is to cover the cost of
the plus delivery routes. Tax is not applicable in this case.
c. [Tax] 0 AND [Delivery fee] 0, 5 or 9 EUR
17 line items just with Food total, Tax and Delivery fee (7 or 10% of the Food total).
These line items have a delivery fee percentage instead of the xed fees. We can also
see tax here, which leads us to assume these are food deliveries.
The only other thing we have in some of the rows are the tips, which are not outstanding
in any way. Strange that there is no card cost either.
Unfortunately, Im not able to gure out how come we have these percentages other
than the x amounts, especially that 15 of these line items are exactly 10.00%.
5
For now Ill treat these items as special deliveries that are maybe harder to deliver
(maybe too cold, too hot or too heavy?).
Its possible that its just a bug - these orders need to be investigated!
d. [Tax] 0 AND [Delivery fee] = 0 AND [Commission] = 0
95 line items without Delivery fee and Commission looking like normal food deliveries.
I assume these items are for having special agreements or partnerships with certain
restaurants where the agreement is to not charge commissions for a specic period or
under specic circumstances. This could be part of a promotional campaign or a
long-term partnership strategy.
Within this campaign with the 0 Delivery fees, I assume we offer discounted services to
attract customers as well. Ill call these campaign deliveries.
5. There are 100% discounts (yellow lines), that are still paying the tip to the couriers. From a
business perspective, paying back the delivery fee is a not so protable choice, but paying back
the tips shouldn't be allowed. In these cases Foodpanda pays the tips in an amount that the
customer is freely choosing (for example ID 74). In this case there is 0 cost for using a credit card.
discount = net food + delivery fee + tips + inflation + tax
6. There are a lot of 5 EUR discounts that makes me feel there is a normal delivery fee discount,
even if the delivery fee is a x 9 EUR. Maybe there was a campaign for this as well providing 5
EUR coupons.
7. We charge the commission fee by line item for non-partner restaurants (when the amount in
Commission column is not 0). Percentage varies per restaurant.
8. Refunds are paid either fully or partially. Full refunds pay back the order value to customers (for
example ID 79). Logical, since this is everything that the customer paid originally.
full refund = net food + delivery fee + tips + inflation + tax
9. Since full refunds (yellow lines) pay back the order value, if there was any discount that would
decrease the amount paid by the customer, we still pay the order value, losing the discounted
amount (for example ID 605). This is not OK and needs to be corrected as it decreases our
revenue.
10. About ination, its quite hard to make good assumptions as there are many examples in todays
economy that prices can do insane increases on a day on day movement - perhaps this is why this
column is something important to be considered.
6
We know if there is a full refund or a full discount customers are paid back with the ination (pls
see #5 and #8). This means that the Food column is most probably not the price that is shown to
the customer.
Therefore, the Tax must be considered in the ination as well, because the tax must be calculated
on the real net food prices.
inflation = inflated amount on net food + tax
total gross food = net food + tax + inflation
Its ne if we dont have the new dataset considering the inated amounts - if we know the
variances by line items (= Ination column), and we have the true tax amount (pls see #13), we
are safe to calculate it ourselves.
11. The rate of ination for each line item varies between 0 and 21%, and its not clearly coming from
the total gross price. I assume this is because each food group has a predetermined ination rate
for a period. In this case its impossible to calculate the period so I assume the ination rate is
calculated from the previous month.
12. There are 5,106 line items with 0% ination (out of 21,755 line item), which can lead us to two
assumptions:
a. either the selected food groups have no ination from the previous month
b. or we are not considering a full month from the rst day of each month till its last day
However, the task clearly states that we consider Month X - so a full month -, therefore we can
assume the best case scenario, that we dont have to inate our prices for every food group or
order.
13. The problem we just discovered with the Ination column suggests that the Tax column is not the
true tax amount the customer pays, but part of it is included in the ination.
Meaning that, if we want to calculate the accurate net food prices with the tax, we need to know
the exact tax rates.
These tax rates are between 7 and 18%.
Out of this dataset its impossible to calculate the inated amounts for net food and tax, because
it seems like that the tax rate varies within the food groups.
Analyzing the quartiles, we can say that
25% of the food orders are below 9.26% tax rate,
25% of the food orders are above 10.05% tax rate,
while the median tax rate is 9.80%.
7
Meanwhile the average tax rate is 9.70%.
If we would like to use a more accurate Food total and Tax for further analysis, we could use this
average tax rate to calculate the inated portions of the Food totals. However, we should keep in
mind that this would be just an estimate.

Revenue earned by our delivery services from customers. This is closely tied to the platforms

Revenue generated by charging a compensation for connecting customers with restaurants and

total commission for non-partners = total commission
Excluding error category!
COGS:
1. Total Courier Cost as signicant operational expenses. This has a direct impact on the
protability of each delivery.
total courier cost = (number of deliveries * 5 EUR) + tips
Excluding remuneration and error category!
Ill ignore the tips received from customers, as it goes 100% to the couriers so it doesnt change
the calculation.
2. Total Support Cost as general running of the organization, providing support to customers and
managing services effectively.
total support cost = (total number of orders * 0.50 EUR)
Assuming that we pay support cost for every line item, we need to consider the total count.
3. Total Card Processing Fee as these charges incur when electronic payments are made by
customers using credit or debit cards. We should keep in mind that the remuneration of the

not able to tell how much we would need to adjust the total fee, because we dont have enough

in the Dataset Edits section.
Total estimated credit card processing fee = (total order value * 1.8%) +
(number of food orders * 0.40 EUR) + (partner remuneration)

ANALYSIS
Gross Prot is a nancial metric that measures the protability of the company's primary operating
activities by subtracting the direct costs from the generated revenue associated with core activities. This
metric doesnt consider other operating expenses such as marketing costs, administrative costs or taxes.
In this example we have an approximate gross prot of 46,134.27 EUR having a total of 21,755 line
items. Since we dont have historical data nor industry benchmarks, this doesnt tell us how healthy our
company is.
We can calculate the gross prot margin which indicates how much prot it makes after accounting for the
direct costs associated with doing business. In our case this is 23.62%, which is considered extremely low.
This could indicate that the operating efciency and/or the cost management is dangerously in critical
shape. However, we should keep in mind that these are very approximate numbers as two very important
things are missing from the calculation: the partner restaurants remunerations, the revenue from the
campaign delivery and the accurate card processing fees.
If we check the COGS percentage (=COGS/Net sales) we get 76.38%, which means that approximately
this much of the Net sales is used to cover the COGS. This indicates that the costs we were able to take
into consideration are impacting the protability, as we cannot consider the gross prot margin healthy.
I believe at this point its clear why we are missing the revenue and the cost side of the weekly
remunerations. On the other hand, campaign delivery is a topic I haven't touched yet. In these kinds of
campaigns, the companies can offer special promotions, discounts or other incentives to attract new
customers and restaurants. While this can increase the deliveries (and can lead to company growth), it
may not directly contribute to the gross prot because there's no immediate commission revenue earned.
It can happen that the companies sign contracts with the restaurants that the rst deliveries are free from
commissions. In our case we dont really know whats behind these line items - so for Month X, we can
only report the cost side of this campaign.
Also, there was another campaign where the old customers could get a 5 EUR discount on the delivery
fee if they successfully make a referral of a new customer. This is something that is very hard to lter out
from the dataset as the Customer Care Team can make various discounts for a lot of orders without the
Finance Team knowing the exact reasons. This campaign neither has immediate revenue, but it can
11
contribute effectively to the brand awareness and customer loyalty that could be an excellent result for a
long-term strategy.
For a more comprehensive analysis of the overall nancial health, we would need to consider other
nancial metrics and examine a complete set of nancial statements. The Income statement, the Balance
sheet and the Cash ow statement could be checked alongside with a breakdown of revenues and
expenses for both partner and non-partner restaurants.
The other issue we have that has decreased the gross prot is regarding the discounts and the refunds.
We could see (assumption #5 and #9) that in case of a full discount the customers get back the tips as
well. Meaning that at the end of the day Foodpanda pays the tips to the couriers in whatever amount the
customer chose to give, without getting it compensated from the customer. This must be corrected.
Regarding the full refund, there are a few cases when the customer paid a discounted amount on their
order, but they received the full order value back. Meaning that the company paid back more to the
customers than they originally paid. This is a bug again, that must be corrected.
There were a couple of line items that were incorrect or needed further checking. Its very important to
make sure that our processes are correctly taking into consideration every event, even if some of them are
so rare that shouldn't exist.
Seeing the current results, I recommend exploring opportunities to improve operational efciency,
optimize costs and to evaluate the effectiveness of the campaigns.

4. Foodpanda attracted 2,500 new customers through SEM marketing efforts in Month X, at an
acquisition cost of 2 per customer. Foodpanda offers First Delivery Discounts for new customers, up to a
maximum of 5 per delivery. On average, these new customers placed 1.8 deliveries in Month X. Please
calculate the revenue and any associated costs accordingly.
COST
Customer acquisition = 2,500 customer * 2 EUR / customer = 5,000 EUR
Total average delivery = 2,500 customer * 1.8 delivery / customer = ~4,500 deliveries
Total discount amount = 4,500 deliveries * 5 EUR / delivery = ~22,500 EUR
Total cost of new customers (approximately) = Customer acquisition + Total discount amount
= 5,000 EUR + 22,500 EUR = ~27,500 EUR
REVENUE
Calculating the revenue before the discounts would look like as the following:
Revenue per customer (before discount) = average number of delivery/customer * average delivery
fee/delivery
14
Total Average Revenue (before discount)
= Revenue per customer (before discount) * Number of acquired customers
= (1.8 * average delivery fee/delivery) * 2,500
And after applying the discounts:
Total Average Revenue (after discount) = Total Average Revenue (before discount) - Total discount
amount
= [(1.8 * average delivery fee/delivery) * 2,500] - 22,500
The revenue side could be calculated as the above example shows, if the average delivery fee/delivery is
known.
